<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-155-076  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 155 076.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Today's Office  Jan 1990 v24 n8 p9(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Taking the guesswork out of networking. (planning a local areanetwork) (Facilities Management)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Levy, Joel; Miller, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A knowledge of microcomputer local area networks (LANs) isbecoming necessary for facilities managers, who must work withcommunications and MIS directors to plan and implement thesystems.andP;  Among the aspects to consider when planning a LAN arethe type of systems to be networked, the type of network to beinstalled, user training and the cabling to be used.andP;  The threetypes of cables used to connect LANs are coaxial cable, which isthe wire used by most cable television hookups; twisted-pairwiring, which is commonly used by telephones; and fiber-opticcable, which supports more signals and faster processing speeds,but which is also more difficult to install and more expensive.andO;Factors to consider when selecting network cabling are discussed.andO;The most common network topologies are bus, ring and star; each isdescribed.andP;  Also described are collision avoidance and servers,bridges and gateways.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Local Area NetworksNetwork ArchitectureComparisonHardware SelectionCablesFacility ManagementPlanning.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>